At 03:26 PM 8/15/2005, you wrote:
&gt;Mike Schwartz wrote:
&gt; &gt; hi,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I notice that Heretrix 1.5.0 (taken from the HEAD last week) outputs
&gt; &gt; a down-counting demonimator in the downloaded/queued document
&gt; &gt; ratio.  For example I started a crawl with 2407 seeds, and it
&gt; &gt; initially grew as new pages were discovered, but after a few minutes
&gt; &gt; it reported that I was on page 568 of 593... making it hard to get a
&gt; &gt; sense of what the real % complete is
&gt;
&gt;It&#39;s been this way for a while: URIs that were scheduled, but then
&gt;&#39;disregarded&#39; don&#39;t count as either pending or completed.
&gt;
&gt;The most notable cause of &#39;disregarded&#39; URIs is those that are
&gt;precluded by robots.txt rules -- they get scheduled, but are never
&gt;attempted, and so should neither count as successful, failed, or
&gt;still-pending.
&gt;
&gt;If you&#39;ve added other settings which can cause URIs to be
&gt;ignored after having been initially scheduled -- such as
&gt;narrowing the scope midcrawl, resulting in URIs that get
&gt;ruled out-of-scope on rechecking -- that will also cause
&gt;URIs to be disregarded, and the total &#39;queued&#39; will decrease
&gt;without the &#39;completed&#39; changing.
&gt;
&gt;This area of the crawler needs improvement; the current
&gt;tallies of &#39;percent done&#39; and &#39;estimated time remaining&#39;
&gt;take no account of the potential for more URIs to be
&gt;discovered, and so are almost worse-than-useless.
&gt;
&gt;I think tracking the effective rates of discovery versus
&gt;completion -- and the rates of change of each -- could
&gt;offer more meaningful estimates, for both the whole crawl
&gt;and individual queues. Some notes on possible approaches
&gt;are on the crawler wiki [*] here:
&gt;
&gt; 
&gt;&lt;http://crawler.archive.org/cgi-bin/wiki.pl?CrawlAndQueueDynamics&gt;http://crawler.archive.org/cgi-bin/wiki.pl?CrawlAndQueueDynamics
&gt;
&gt;But, implementing some of these ideas is not yet a priority
&gt;for any upcoming releases, so it would take someone interested
&gt;in this area to contribute some code for the situation to
&gt;improve in the short term.
&gt;
&gt;- Gordon @ IA
&gt;
&gt;[*] Reminder: the crawler wiki edit password is available on
